We exploit exogenous variation in years of completed college induced by 
draft-avoidance behavior during the Vietnam War to examine the impact of college 
on adult mortality. Our estimates imply that increasing college attainment from 
the level of the state at the 25th percentile of the education distribution to 
that of the state at the 75th percentile would decrease cumulative mortality for 
cohorts in our sample by 8 to 10 percent relative to the mean. Most of the 
reduction in mortality is from deaths due to cancer and heart disease. We also 
explore potential mechanisms, including differential earnings and health 
insurance.

